                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">do not personally agree with a lot of the ideas that Drex is offering, but to me it sounds like he tries to live by many of the ideas this country was originally founded on.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Uhhuh.  Sure.  Unfortunately, you're wrong.<br /><br />During the Whiskey Rebellion a bunch of Appalachian Hillbillies (just like Drex) proclaimed their right to refuse to pay taxes that THEY considered unjust and unconstitutional.  George Washington himself called out the army and marched it out to crush the rebellion, shot a bunch of people, then put the surviving ringleaders on trial. And the people who lead the Revolution cheered him on.<br /><br />That's because everyone understood that in a democracy elected officals and the courts are responsible for framing, interpreting, and enforcing the law.  Easily excitable, semi-literates don't get to appoint themselves to the job, and then unilaterally declare the laws don't apply to them.  Thats not 'rugged individualism'.  Its 'criminal behavior' at best and 'attempting to overthrow a democratically elected government' at its worst.<br /><br />Our elected officials and the courts, in their wisdom, have decided we have to pay income taxes.  The constitution was amended to specifically allow it, even though an income tax had been used on and off for decades prior to the amendment.  _LEGAL_ efforts to claim the amendment is invalid, and hence the taxes are invalid, have all failed.  Individuals don't get to 'opt out' because they think they've discovered a legal loophole, any more than they can 'opt out' of the their local criminal code or the Clean Air Act.<br /><br />Sometimes people DO manage to convince judges and juries that they are so stupid and confused they don't actually belong in jail for refusing to pay.  But they still HAVE TO PAY TAXES.  And they have to pay the financial penalties, too, if they pay late.<br /><br />The IRS may not notice you immediately, but they will notice eventually....then your financial life will be mud for the rest of your life....assuming you stay out of jail.<br /><br />/shrug<br /><br />Don't believe me?  Fine.  Set your withholding allowances high, stop filing your returns, then wait ten years and see what happens.  Don't say you weren't warned, though.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
