l likely be "nannied" by their insurance companies far better than they're currently "taken care of" by the Nanny-State.  It'd probably be a helluva lot cheaper, too, being that competition would be allowed to drive the market.  I certainly don't see people working 4-6 months out of the year to pay for it in a competitive free market.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br />That's not to mention your example is stupid.  All of my food and/or drugs have <b>already</b> been tested, and that's why I know they're safe to eat and/or take.  The FDA only regulates controlled substances.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />And who makes them "controlled substances" ? And if my example is stupid because all your food and drugs have already been tested, why doesn't that make your example (using the FDA) stupid?  I mean, if everything you're using and planning on using is already tested, what are you paying the FDA for?<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br />You could box up a pile of dog shit, and put it in your pantry, eat it when you wish.  No jackbooted thugs are going to come stop you.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />In most states somebody could go to a judge and have me commited at the State's behest for a minimal 3 day evaluation for such things.  Wow, I'd never thought of it before, but I'm not even free to "eat shit and die" should I so choose.  Thanks, I'll have to use that one <img src="images/jester_125.gif" border="0" alt="" title="" align="middle" /><br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br />What you <b>can't</b> do is sell it to someone else telling them it will cure arthritis.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quot