 saying he tries to live his life by "the idea of rugged individualism that many of our forefathers lived and preached" is kind of gooshie, don't you think?<br /><br />And to be honest, we should all be skeptical about the whole 'rugged individualism" thing anyway.  The first thing most pioneers did once they had cleared a homestead was help build community organizations and buildings: militias, churches, schools and town councils.  The whole idea of the 'rugged individual' seems to have sprang up after the frontier was closed.  It was a product of dime novels about the frontier, not the frontier itself.<br /><br />Hell....most of the pioneers settled plots that had been surveyed off first by the federal government.  And they were given the land, FOR NOTHING, by Uncle Sam.  The settlement of the USA's western frontier was one of the biggest government-run welfare schemes in history.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
