nk for one moment that the cost that manufacturer incur getting products tested and approved isn't passed on to you? If you don't, then perhaps it is a bit more clear why you ran your perfectly good business into the ground.<br /><br />Not only that, but I can guarantee you that at least 25% of the population of the US (probably upwards of 50%, maybe even more) don't have a fricking clue what the Underwriters Laboratory is, or what it does.  They don't give a rats ass if the little UL symbol is on their curling iron.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br /><br />Additionally, due to a fear of lawsuits for selling faulty products, many retailers refuse to carry products that haven't undergone some kind of testing.  Go into Office Depot or Staples n see how many desk lamps they carry that aren't UL approved.<br /><br /><b>Proof-positive that the free-market can provide for product safety testing.</b><br /><br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Lawsuits?  How the hell are you going to sue someone after you dismantle the government?  Now all of the sudden you want the judges and courts and regulations?  Come on, which is it?  Either you want them or you don't.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br /><br />You'd probably get sued for everything you have.  If that in and of itself didnt put you right out of business, once word got out that your product killed or maimed people you'd be pretty well done for, dontcha think?<br /><br />(THINK being the key word in all of this)<br /><br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Well, in our current society, yes, you sue a company that doesn't comply with standards, the only agency that is going to enforce the standards and/or legal actions is the <b>government</b>.  <br 