ay that the people who have insurance would pay for it, and the rest of the people in the free market wouldn't have anything to do with you because you don't have insurance.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br /><br />Who said we don't have a filtration system?<br /><br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />I don't care if you do or don't.  The fact of the matter is there is an agency that you can contact that will give the information of how to safely treat your water.  You would pay for this service whether it is private or governmental.  The only difference is since the information is provided by the government and it's already been paid for, it doesn't seem like a big deal to you.<br /><br />If you privatize, then the information becomes valuable.  Not only would you not have any idea on how to treat your water, you'd get charged through the fricking nose in order for someone to set it up for you.  Wanna know why you'd get charged so much?  It's because only the people with wells would have to pay, making the cost much higher to those individuals.  You're going to pay no matter what you do.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br />Oh, you <b>do</b> appriciate our standing military then?  <b>Start paying for it you leech!</b><br /><br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />I didnt say that, either.  I said it should be open to private markets.<br /><br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Ahh yes, let's put the world's most powerful military into the hands of people who have absolutely no vested interest in what the population of the country thinks.<br /><br />At least GWB has to make it <i>look</i> like he's doing what is best for the nation.  As soon as it moves to private hands, who is going to put a check on what the military does?  Remember, private individuals don't get elected.<br /><br />Regardless... you would <b>still have to pay for it!</b><br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br /><br />But thanks to our volunteer fire department, such a need won't arise.  Where's our tax break?  Besides, I think that's a silly argument.  There's an auto mechanic down the road to fix my worthless car, should the need arise.  Should I be paying him a percentage out of all my financial transactions, just because he's there?<br /><br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />If your local government doesn't have to spend as much money on fire trucks, then the local budget won't be as high, thus they won't need to tax you as heavily on every tranaction you make.  You <b>do</b> get a break if they don't need to spend the money.<br /><br />I'm also willing to bet that your volunteer fire department isn't all you've cracked it up to be.  More likely, it is a bunch of people who volunteer to help the "real" fire department if they run into something they need extra man power for.  For <i>real</i> emergencies, I'm sure there is a paid, professional fire department on call 24/7.<br /><br />Your mechanic analogy is quite flawed as well.  First of all, if you take your car to the mechanic, you have to <b>pay</b> him to fix it.  The fire department will not send you a bill when your lean-to burns down and they have to put it out.  If the fire department <i>did</i> send out bills (because they were privatized) you can bet your sweet ass the bills would be a hell of a lot more than you pay in taxes.  Then guess what happens?  You have to pay more on your fire insurance to cover the fire department bill, and the fire department would no longer go to homes that couldn't prove they could pay.<br /><br />Secondly, if your car is broken down at 3AM, you wait til the next morning to get it fixed.  That doesn't work for fire departments, they need to be there 24/7.  Wouldn't it be wonderful if you privatized all of the governmental agencies?  I would just love to dial 911 and the first thing I hear is "credit card number please".<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br /><br />Why are you stuck on this "living off the land" thing? Believe it or not, we DO have grocery stores and running water out here.<br /><br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Because you keep giving examples of your hillbilly small town.  Your volunteer fire department might be adequate for Timbuktoo in the middle of backwater Tennessee, but it isn't going to work for a city with millions of people.  You are trying to apply these micro fixes to macro issues.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br /><br />I agree 100% that society needs rules, and have posted in great depth on the subject in the OT forum.  You should read up on my political theory before trying to attack it.<br /><br />My contention, however (and the contention of many others, some far more educated than I) is that a free market would do a much better job of providing most services that the State currently holds an artificial monopoly on.<br /><br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />But your political theory doesn't alleviate the problems that you think you face.  There would still be jackbooted thugs keeping you from selling dangerous materials to others, there would still need to be fire departments.  Those thugs and agencies would still need to be paid for, and they would still protect you whether you like it or not.<br /><br />The only thing that would shift is that you'd be complaining about company ABC instead of the government.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br /><br />Take up my slack to provide me with what?  And who's fault is that?  <br /><br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />I've already explained several things that are provided to you. You seem to think that if the government didn't do them, they would get done by an all powerful "free market".  <br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br /><br />The State is a thief, and you are both its willing victim and it's accomplice.  You are its stooge; I, on the other hand, am a real American trying to promote capitalism.<br /><br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Whatever I am, you sir are a criminal, and you're promoting criminal ideas.  If your ideas are so good, why haven't we switched over to them?  Aren't the peope who vote the same Americans that you don't think would ever fall for any type of scam, could never be swindled, and thus don't need any type of protection.  Why aren't politicians with your ideas in charge of the country?<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br /><br />What do you do for society?  Pay your taxes? So did Ted Bundy.<br /><br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Yes, I pay my taxes, I <b>contribute</b>.  You, on the other hand, don't do shit, you <b>leech</b>.  In the taxes department, Ted Bundy was indeed better than you are.  Just like Ted Bundy, even if you <i>did</i> pay your taxes, you would still need to go to prison for breaking the law.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br /><br />At least I'm offering equitable, cost-effective alternatives.  I don't see you trying to argue for or demonstrate that the bloated State-monopoly on services really makes people better off, I see you hurling insults about hillbillies and vermin-infested shacks.  I don't think that's doing much to prove me wrong.<br /><br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />You aren't offering squat, your ideas won't work because they aren't thought out far enough.  There are reasons things are done they way they are, whether you realize them or not.  To even pretend that you have some small semblance of an idea on how to run a nation of almost 300 million people all by yourself is absurd.  There are so many factors that are involved that you don't even have a clue about it is pitiful.  <br /><br />You haven't proven anything, you haven't shown that privatizing every aspect of the government will help anything.  All you've done is complain that you're getting services you don't want, even though you go back and want to utilize those services once you need them.<br /><br />The bottom line is that if the government didn't <i>require</i> hospitals (more specifically emergency rooms) to take in people regardless of whether they can pay or not, you'd probably be dead.  The free market would have dictated that the chances are you couldn't pay, so you would have been turned away.  Since no reputable doctor would have seen you (because you didn't have insurance), you would have been left with whatever you could find.  You might have been able to find some anibiotics, but who knows?  With no FDA to regulate drugs, you might have been sold sugar pills by a charlatan.  <br /><br />The idea of privatization of <i>some</i> government agencies in of itself isn't really all that bad, but the way you present it is stupid.  Your views are so extreme that they no longer make any sense.  To argue that the privatization of some government agencies might lower the burden on the tax payer is a noble idea if one can find a way to do so without endagering the citizens.  To say the government is robbing the citizens blind for no reason is simply stupidity.  To claim that you don't get anything you want for your tax dollars is dumb.  Yes, you probably pay for some things that you'll never use, but lots of other people have paid for things that you <i>do</i> use.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
